value.value: A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the allelic gain of all or part of chromosome 17.
A chromosomal abnormality consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 7 in somatic cells.

A cytogenetic abnormality involving chromosome 17 that results from loss of the short arm and duplication of the long arm. This aberration is associated with a variety of neoplastic diseases, and is indicative of a poor prognosis for individuals with hematologic malignancies.
A fluid filled sac within the cerebrum. It is can be congenital, trauma related or secondary to another medical condition for example an infarction.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to allelic gain of all or part of the chromosomal arm 20q.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to allelic gain of all or part of the chromosomal arm 15q.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to allelic gain within the chromosomal arm 1q.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to allelic gain of all or part of the chromosomal arm 9q.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the duplication of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 17.
A molecular abnormality indicating the presence of an abnormally high level of the G1/S-specific cyclin-D1 protein.
A chromosomal abnormality that refers to the gain of genetic material in the long arm of chromosome 8.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to allelic gain of all or part of the chromosomal arm 5q.
A granuloma located on the conjunctiva, usually involving the inner surface of the eyelid.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of chromosome 14.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of chromosome 22.
The presence of genomic instability associated with defective DNA mismatch repair in greater than 30% of the microsatellite instability (MSI) biomarkers in a tumor sample.
Genomic instability associated with the presence of hypermutation either in one microsatellite instability (MSI) marker or in between 10 and 30 percent of the MSI markers in a tumor sample.
A chromosomal abnormality consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 2 in somatic cells.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 18 (18q).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 13 (13q).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 12 (12q).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the short arm of chromosome 17 (17p).

The actetate salt form of chlormadinone, a synthetic progestin with antiandrogenic and antigonadotropic effects. Chlormadinone acetate (CMA) is a potent progesterone receptor (PR) agonist, a partial androgen receptor (AR) antagonist and a weak glucocorticoid receptor (GR) antagonist. Chlormadinone binds to PRs, which induces the expression of progesterone-responsive genes. In addition, chlormadinone blocks ARs in target organs and reduces the activity of skin 5 alpha-reductase; thus inhibiting androgen production and signaling. Through the negative feedback action on the hypothalamus-pituitary system, chlormadinone also suppresses gonadotropin secretion, which prevents ovarian and adrenal androgen production. Therefore, this agent decreases endometrial thickness, increases the viscosity of cervical mucus, inhibits ovulation and suppresses follicular growth and maturation.
Abnormal fluid filled sac within the conjunctiva.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the short arm of chromosome 6 (6p).

A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the short arm of chromosome 1 (1p). It has been described in gliomas, meningiomas, neuroblastomas, hepatocellular carcinomas, breast carcinomas, acinar prostate adenocarcinomas, pancreatic carcinomas, and adrenal gland adenomas.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the short arm of chromosome 3.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the short arm of chromosome 8 (8p).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of chromosome 6.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the short arm of chromosome 11 (11p).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 22 (22q).
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 19 (19q). It has been described in gliomas and hemangiopericytomas.
A chromosomal abnormality consisting of the absence of one of the copies of chromosome 17.

A condition characterized by the formation of fatty deposits under the skin in the area of the eyelids. These well-demarcated growths, more common in women than men and sometimes hereditary, may indicate elevated cholesterol levels in the blood or the fatty degeneration of the superficial fibers of the orbicularis muscle.
